column168: E Gutierrez, MofW Foreman reported at 1525 on 03/06/2007 that he spotted a leaking tank car ( NATX300316, placarded un1170)on N-33 track at Joliet.  Yardmaster Dick Rogers drove to the seen and observed product leaking at a rate of 5 drops/10 sec.  Mr. Rogers was instructed by the Envirnomental Engineer to place a buckek under the leak, and that the area should be kept clear of personnel and equipment in a 150ft. zone.  Flash point of material was 55degrees.  Weather was clear with a westerly breeze and temp of 29degree.  Shipper,Grain Processing of Muscatine Iowa, was notified of leak and they contacted their contractor ( ResCar )to go the the EJ&E RR to fix the leaking car.  Jeff Hood of ResCar was dispatched at 1730 to fix the leaking car.  Loose bolts were found at the value under the car to be the cause of the leak.  Bolts were tightened and visual contact was given for thirty minutes to confirm proper repairs were performed.  The leaking product of ethanol was captured in a five gallon bucket ( about 1 gallon ) was removed from the property by Jeff Hood for proper disposal.  Track was blue flagged by car Dept at the start of the incident.  Track back in service at 1900 hrs.
UNABLE TO DETERMINE CAUSE OF DAMAGE.  NO VISIBLE DAMAGE TO THE BOX.

column168: Our driver was headed down Highway 87 near Lewistown, Mt.  We came to the conclusion that innattentive driving caused the rear trailer tandems to go off the road and shifted the product inside the tanker and causing it to rollover.  When it rolled over the washout port cap located on the manhole loosened and started to leak.  The Fire Department/Hazmat response on scene had sand hauled in to contain the product that leaked into the ditch.  A state certified water agency came and drew the water out and brought that to a recylcing center.  We had another carrier & hazmat team come on sight and transfer the product into their trailer drawing out of the external valve and then the manway after the product level got low enough.  Trailer was uprighted and towed away.  We have the emergency team currently remediating the soil and hauling it away...new soil fill is being brought in.

column168: Driver had completed deliveries from the day and was returning to his domicile in Starke FL.  The driver stated that at or about 1600 he side swiped a parked vehicle that was located in the emergency lane at mile marker 335 on I-95N causing him to crash.  The crash resulted in his cargo, consiting of one 4x1 gallon fiberboard case of Sulfuric Acid 38% (UN2796) refered to as "pool acid", a 5 gallon pail of Trichloroisocyanuric acid "pool tablets" (UN2468), one 4x1 gallon fiberboard case of liquid ammonia (UN2672) and residual Sodium Hypochlorite (UN1791 Bleach 10%), being thrown from the vehicle and damaged on impack with the roadway.    At 1702, contacted the State Warning Point who had already been notified by HAZMAT.  HAZMAT arrived on scene and cleared in incident at 1739.  HAZMAT estimated 3.5 gallons of Sulfuric Acid 38%, 35 gallons of Sodiuom Hypochlorite residue, 3.5 gallons of Liquid Ammonia and 10 pounds of Trichloroisocyanuric Acid.    Dumont had dispatched a company truck to the scene to assist in cleanup.    At 1802, FLDEP ER 904-591-4060 assessed the scene and advised neutralization in place to address the spilled products.    Dumont arrived on scene to address spill.  Used Sodium Bicarbonate to neutralize acid, used Calcium Thiosulfate to neutralize bleach.  Pool tablets were picked up.       Cleanup was assessed by DEP and cleared.

column168: On March 12, 2007, one 300-Gallon tote of Sodium Hydroxide Solution 50% tipped over at 1717 E Fargo Ave, Nampa, ID. Earl Kane was staging materials in preparation to load a curtain van trailer for a shipment. While moving a 300 gallon tote of Sodium Hydroxide Solution 50% with the fork lift, he turned a corner too quickly (he was traveling on a slightly downgraded slope), and the tote began to tip. He lowered the tote to the ground, but the tote still tipped over. The tote is constructed of two pieces: the outer plastic shell and the inner plastic bladder. The outer shell was undamaged by the fall, but the top of the inner shell cracked. The top of the tote fractured and the flowing material opened a hole about 18-24 inches in diameter in the top of the bladder.  Earl quickly turned the tote upright, but 250-275 gallons of material had  leaked out.    The material ran down the asphalt into open soil. Earl quickly covered the material and the soil with an absorbent material. BHS contacted the appropriate emergency response agencies, the NRC, the Idaho Department of Environmental Quality, and Environmental Management Solutions, to assist with the clean-up. BHS rented a mini-excavator and collected the contaminated soil and absorbent. The area was rinsed with a non-hazardous citric acid solution and the rinsates were combined with the collected soil and absorbent.    The soil, absorbent, and rinsates were collected in lined containment totes. BHS worked with Enviromental Management Solutions of Meridian, ID, during all of the clean up and remediation. The totes were taken for proper disposal at a certified waste treatment facility by Environmental Management Solutions.    The spill was completely contained to BHS property at 1717 E. Fargo Ave. The soil has since been replaced with fresh clean material.
column169: BHS has determined that Earl Kane was traveling too rapidly on the fork lift. BHS is planning to put all of its employees through a refresher course on fork lift safety.

File - 07-130 DOT    Shipper - US Mex Drug & Alcohol    AWB# - HRL 3077868.5825 NEW     On 03/06/2007 at 0238, a leaking shipment was reported in “F” building of the ILN main sort facility, located at ABX Air, Inc., 145 Hunter Drive, Wilmington, OH 45177. Spill technician donned proper personal protective equipment and responded. Upon arrival, he found a lab pack with visible signs of leakage on the inside of the package. He removed the package from the area and began his investigation. Upon this investigation, he found this package to contain 16 x 3 ounce plastic specimen cups of Biological Substances, Category B. This shipment was marked incorrectly as a Diagnostic Specimen.      Clear of scene: 0317     There are picture on file in the hazardous materials office in Wilmington, Ohio.

column168: At approximately 15:30 on March 7, 2007 a van trailer that was being staged for off-loading at Clean Harbors Environmental Services Facility located in Chicago, IL experienced a minor release of hazardous waste material from a non-bulk package.  While off loading the trailer, an employee noticed small amount of material on the floor of the van trailer.  He immediately notified his supervisor of the spill and an in house emergency response crew was dispatched to identify the source of release and to take all necessary corrective actions.  Upon review of the paperwork, the emergency response crew donned appropriate protective equipment and entered the trailer.  An inspection of the non-bulk packages in the trailer identified that a single 55-gallon UN 1A1 container of Division 6.1 solution experienced a small pinhole on the bottom of the drum.  The cause of the pinhole is unknown but possibly caused by a protruding nail of a pallet.  The response crew immediately used a chemically compatible absorbent material to contain approximately 2 gallons of liquid that was release to the floor of the trailer.   The leaking drum was placed in a suitable salvage drum and all of the absorbent was collected and placed into appropriate container for disposal at an approved hazardous waste management facility.  The released material was confined to the inside of the van trailer and no offsite impact occurred.
column169: Our investigation determined that the cause of the incident was a small pinhole in the bottom portion of the drum possibly caused by protruding part of a pallet or other small sharp foreign object during the course of loading or transportation.      Drivers will be reminded to thoroughly inspect floorboards, loading devices and pallets, when used for any damage, protrusions or debris that may cause abrasion or punctures.

column168: File - 07-27 DOT & OMC  Shipper - Acuity Brands 353  AWB# - RIV 72325102780 JBS    On 03/07/2007 at 1245 EST, the Hazardous Materials Hotline received a phone call from the Fresno Sort Hub, located at 3688 East Central Avenue, Fresno, CA 93725. Employee from the Fresno Sort Hub reported that they had a leaking and odorous shipment. The Hotline contacted HMHTTC spill response team. Upon arrival, they found a fiberboard box containing 12 xl quart plastic bottles of On &Off (Liquid) Oven and Grill Cleaner. While being loaded into a truck for departure, the box fell out of the truck causing the product to leak a total of 4 quarts. This shipment arrived into Fresno via truck #4376.    This shipment was not declared as a regulated hazardous material.    Clear of scene: 2350 EST

column168: Truck/Cargo Tank was heading east on a straight black top county road when the truck drove off onto the sandy soft shoulder, sucked into the ditch and rolled over. The driver was taken by EMS to the Morton County Hospital and was released the next day. The NCRA Emergency Response Team responded to the incident and safely off loaded and righted the vehicle.    The cargo tank was buckled on the right side between multiple ring stiffners but the unit did not fail. All hazardous material was contained inside the cargo tank.
column169: The driver is currently off duty pending completion of the incident. NCRA has an extensive training program. NCRA will continue to educate the drivers on the risk of distractions while driving.     If the drivers employment is continued, he will be required to attend a professional evaluation and remedial actions will be taken accordingly.    No recommendation on the specification cargo tank construction.     NCRA installs blank flanges or each side at each end of the cargo tank to facilitate off loading during these incidents. This makes off loading of the HM much safer and dramatically reduces the time it takes to off load.

column168: File -07-15 FAA & DOT Shipper - Intl Bonded Couriers AWB# - TMB 00237739252 BDL    On 03/08/2007 at 0417, a leaking shipment was reported in “A” building of the ILN main sort facility, located at ABX Air, Inc., 145 Hunter Drive, Wilmington, Ohio 45177. Spill technicians donned proper personal protective equipment and responded. Upon arrival, they found a fiberboard box with visible signs of leakage on the outside of the package and emitting an odor. They removed the package from the area and began the investigation. Upon this investigation, they found this package to contain a metal part that had an unknown amount of gasoline still inside. Due to no closure on the part to contain the gasoline, a total of 8 ounces of the product was lost. This shipment arrived into Wilmington via flight #0165, N8O5DH. This incident was reported to the Great Lakes Region Federal Aviation Administration.  This shipment was not declared as a regulated hazardous material.  Clear: 0508  There are pictures on file in the Hazardous Materials office in Wilmington, Ohio.

column168: UTLX 500022 INSIDE THE BNSF GALESBURG REPAIR FACILITY FOR REPAIRS TO BROKEN DRAFT LUGS IN THE DRAFT GEAR ASSEMBLY; AND FRICTION WEAR PLATE REPLACEMENT AT THE TRUCK ASSEMBLY, WAS REPORTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC).  ALL PERSONNEL INSIDE THE REPAIR FACILITY CEASED WORK AND EVACUATED THE BUILDING.  A BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDER REPORTED FINDING THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVE HANDLE HAD EXCESSIVE PLAY AND THE HANDLE'S PINNING MECHANISM FAILED TO FULLY SECURE IT FROM MOVEMENT.  THIS POSSIBLE CAUSED THE VALVE TO SLIGHTLY OPEN.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET HANDLE WAS TIE-WRAPPED TO SECURE IT FORM ANY FURTHER MOVEMENT.  THE BOC WAS FOUND TO BE 1 1/4 TURNS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND IT WAS TOOL TIGHTENED.  THE PRODUCT DRIPS STOPPED AFTER SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED AT 1725 HRS.  CST, 3/01/07. THE SPILLAGE THAT DIDN'T EVAPORATE ON THE CONCRETE FLOOR WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.

column168: AN EASTBOUND BNSF TRAIN STOPPED ON THE MAIN TRACK ON A STEEP ASCENDING GRADE AFTER AN EMERGENCY BRAKE APPLICATION.  TRAIN CREW INSPECTION REVEALED A FALLED COUPLER ON AN ENTRAINED RAILCAR AND DURING SETTING HAND BRAKES TO TIE-DOWN THE TRAIN, THE TRAIN CONDUCTOR REPORTED A LPG TYPE ODOR EMANATING FROM ANOTHER ENTRAINED RAILCAR, BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RAPID RESPONDERS WERE DISPATCHED AND INSPECTED ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LADENED RAILCARS IN THE VICINITY OF THE DETECTED ODOR SOURCE.  RESPONDERS COULD NOT FIND THE ODOR SOURCE AND RELEASED THE TRAIN BACK TO THE TRAIN CREW AT 0150 HRS.  PST, THE RAILCAR WITH THE FAILED COUPLER WAS SET-OUT OF THIS TRAIN.  THE RESPONDERS RECHECKED THIS TRAIN AFTER THE CONDUCTOR AGAIN REPORTED THE SAME DETECTABLE ODOR.  DURING THE SECOND INSPECTION, THE RESPONDERS FOUND GATS 53384 WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID PRODUCT AROUND THE MANWAY.  RESPONDERS RESPONDERS REPORTED THA ALL SIX MANWAY SECUREMENT NUTS/BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  RESPONDERS TOOL TIGHTENED THE SECUREMENT NUTS/BOLTS FROM ONE FULL TURN TO 1 1/4 TURNS.  THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE THAT DIDN'T EVAPORATED WAS WIPED.  THE TRAIN WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED AT 0425 HRS. PST. 3/02/07.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO A PETROLEUM BULK PLANT.  THE GAUGE FOR THE TANK WAS UNLEDGEABLE.  THE CUSTOMER ORDERED THE SPECIFIC GALLONS AND ASSURED THE DRIVER THE LOAD WOULD FIT.  WHEN THE DRIVER WAS FINISHING THE DELIVERY, THE TANK STARTED LEAKING AT THE TOP OF THE TANK.  THERE IS APPARENTLY A SEAM AT THE TOP OF THE TANK BY A FILL COVER WHERE THE PRODUCT STARTED SPILLING.  THE AREA AROUND THE TANK IS A CONTAINMENT AREA WITH A RUBBER LINER.  WHEN THE CUSTOMER RETURNED WITH HIS BULK TRUCK, HE DRAINED DOWN SOME OF THE TANK TO STOP THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THERE WAS NOT ANY RELEASE OTHER THAN IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE MN DUTY OFFICER WAS CALLED @ 1355, TALKED TO A REPORTED AND THE SPILL PREPOT WAS FILED.  TALKED TO THE MINNESTOA POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY AROUND 1400.  TOLD THEM THAT THE OWNER TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE RELEASE,  IT WAS CONTAINED AND WOULD BE RECOVERED BY THE CUSTOMER BY PUMPING OUT THE SPILL IN THE CONTAINMENT HOLDING AREA AND PLACING IN A SEPARATE TANK.  MPCA WAS SATISFIED WITH THE SPILL CLEAN-UP BY THE CUSTOMER.  THE SPILL WAS ESTIMATED BY OUR DRIVER TO BE 30 TO 40 GALLONS.  THE CUSTOMER ESTIMATED IT TO BE UNDER 25 GALLONS.

column168: A mixture of acetonitrile, sodium hydroxide, methanol, pyridine, and methylene chloride leaked from the 55 gallon steel shipping container as the result of what appears to be internal corrosion. Of the original 50 gallons in the container at the time of pickup,  responding personnel were able to determine that approximately 0.5 gallons leaked from the container.        The leaking container was one of two that contained the same liquid, and upon inspection revealed a small but noticeable star-shaped indentation on the sidewall of the container, approximately 6 inches down from the top rim.  A thorough inspection of the container revealed several other areas where the paint was noticeably “bubbled.” This might be an indication that the container failed (corroded) from the inside.     At 16:50, approximately 10 minutes after the vehicle arrived at the facility from its pickup route, a Triumvirate employee noticed a small trickle of liquid coming from the side door of the bed of the truck.   The material appeared to have just begun to leak from the side of the truck and there was no evidence that the leak had begun prior to the vehicle arriving at the destination. A close inspection of the immediate road surface showed no evidence that the leak occurred before the vehicle parked.      An empty open-head container was placed directly under the leak to collect the dripping liquid, while at the same time two Triumvirate employees donned Level-B personal protective equipment and entered the vehicle to identify and address the leaking container.  Once inside the vehicle, the Triumvirate employees were able to quickly identify the container in question and immediately placed it into an 85 gallon “over-pack” salvage container. While the two employees worked to contain and clean up the spill in the back of the truck, other Triumvirate responders using appropriate clean up materials addressed the affected area beside the vehicle.  All of the spill response by-products were containerized for subsequent disposal.
column169: For future shipments of this waste material, at the time of acceptance (pick up) Triumvirate employees will perform an even more thorough inspection of the shipping containers to identify before hand any potential container defects.  The “offeror” of the waste was notified of the situation and asked by Triumvirate to inspect their shipping container inventory for any potential defects.  Triumvirate also asked the offeror to re-evaluate their selection process for selecting proper shipping containers.

column168: During normal switching operations in the railyard, UTLX 204519 was reported sloshing a small amount of product from the manway cover. Movement was stopped; and the initial inspection by a BNSF mechanical responder revealed that there was no shipper seal applied to the manway lid and that at least 2 of 6 manway securement swing bolts (at the 9 & 11 o’clock positions) were loose. UTLX 204519 was carefully moved and isolated on the repair tracks in the railyard awaiting shipper contractor response, inspection and securement. On 3/07/07, shipper contract responders from RESCAR reported that all six manway bolts became loose when they began to tool tightened these securement bolts in the recommended pattern. Afterwards, the manway bolts were loosened and manway cover opened to inspect the outage level and the condition of the manway gasket. The manway gasket was deemed in good condition and the product outage was at 4 inches. The manway was closed and properly secured. Response was concluded prior to 1130 hrs. PST, 3/07/07. A BNSF seal numbered 21 56440 was applied at the manway lid. All spillage evaporated on the tank shell and no ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Upon arriving at the 10-day intransit facility located in Port Arthur, Texaes, a Veolia driver noticed liquid coming through the floor of the trailer.  The driver immediately called the Veolia, Port Arthur facility for assistance, at which time, a clean-up crew was dispatched. Prior to offloading, a large amount of clay absorbent was spread on the floor of the trailer to absorb the free liquids and was poured between the drums to absorb any other liquid that might leak.  The under-frame of the trailer and the tires were dried with towels.  The leaking drum was identified and overpacked into a salvage drum.  All spill cleanup material was packaged and transported to the Veolia, Port Arthur facility for incineration.
column169: A packing group II drum was used instead of a packing group I drum as required by the HMR for the material.  The shipper will be informed about utilizing the proper containers and proper filling techniques.  Veolia employees will be re-trained on properly inspecting the containers to ensure the shipper has used the correct packaging.

On March 8,2007, a Brenntag Northeast, Inc. driver called to report that he noticed a leak coming from the trailer while entering the on-ramp of Interstate 81 North, exit number 211. Another Brenntag Northeast, Inc. driver assisted in containing the material. A hazmat team was dispatched to the location and discovered that the outlet valve was loose on the IBC. The rear locknut somehow came loose, or possibly was never properly tightened when manufactured. The response team merely tightenad the locknut and the leak stopped. All materials were packaged, sealed, marked and properly transported to Brenntag Northeast, Inc. for disposal.
column169: No comment.  Brenntag Northeast, Inc. has used thousands of these IBC5 without failure.

column168: At approximately 9:30 am, a Veolia driver arrived at the Veolia, Port Washington, WI terminal to pick up a load of PCB bushings for transport to the Veolia recycling facility located in Phoenix, AZ. Upon inspection of the bushings prior to loading, it was discovered that one bushing was leaking from a pipe/tube located at the top of the bushing that had previously been connected to a gauge or other piping. This pipe had been plugged and duct taped by the offeror prior to delivery to the Port Washington terminal. Since the pipe was a threaded pipe and screwed into the top of the bushing, it was decided that the appropriate corrective action would be to remove the pipe and replace it with a threaded plug. Plugs were purchased and installed in the bushings. While conducting these activities two other bushings began to leak before we could get the plugs installed.     On the date of the incident, the weather conditions in Port Washington were unseasonably warm and it appears that dielectric fluid contained in the bushings began to expand as the bushings warmed up sitting in the sun. This expansion caused the plugs that had been used to fail and a small amount of fluid began to leak from the bushings. It is estimated that less than 0.5 pounds of liquid were released. The area of the release was cleaned using diesel fuel and sampled in accordance with the EPA rules for PCB contaminated oil.

column168: At approximately 3:00 pm on March 20, 2007 a van trailer stored at Clean Harbors Environmental Services 10-day in-transit storage yard located in El Dorado, AR experienced a minor release of hazardous waste material from a non-bulk package.  During a daily inspection, an employee at the location noticed small amount of material seeping through the van trailer floor.  He immediately notified his supervisor of the spill and an in house emergency response crew was dispatched to identify the source of release and to take all necessary corrective actions.  Upon review of the paperwork, the emergency response crew donned appropriate protective equipment and entered the trailer.  An inspection of the non-bulk packages in the trailer identified that a single 5-gallon UN 1A2 container of Class 3 Paint, appeared to have been damaged by the superimposed weight of other similar containers stacked on top of it.  The response crew immediately used a chemically compatible absorbent material to contain approximately 1gallon of liquid that was release to the floor of the trailer.   The leaking container was placed in a suitable salvage drum and all of the absorbent was collected and placed into appropriate container for disposal at an approved hazardous waste management facility.   Approximately one quart of material leaked through the floorboards of the van-trailer onto gravel and compacted dirt pad.  The contaminated area was excavated, the material placed into appropriate containers for disposal at an approved hazardous waste management facility.     The time frame from the initial notice of the spill until the drum was overpacked and the spill clean up was approximately 2 hours.  All of the released material was collected and no offsite impact occurred.
column169: It appears that the superimposed weight of the containers loaded on top of the failed container caused the container to partially crush and release some of its contents.  The offerror of this shipment has been informed of this incident and proper preparation of hazardous materials for shipment will be addressed with the responsible personnel.

column168: On Monday, March 19th at 0650 hours Train 061817 derailed seven cars including UTLX646672 (Load - Sodium Chlorate, Aqueous Solution) while departing Hamlet Yard in Hamlet, North Carolina. Tank Car UTLX646672 rolled off the track structure and came to rest on its BL side at a 90 degree angle. A steady stream (3/4) of liquid began leaking out of the manway area onto the adjacent asphalt roadway and ballast media. CSX Management immediately implemented the corporation’s emergency response plan. A call was placed to Chemtrec (Report # 03192007004) and the shipper, Finnchem USA was notified of the release. CSX Hazardous Material Manager along with representatives from Hepaco Environmental were dispatched to the scene. Once on site attempts were made to contain the release by tightening the manway securement bolts/ nuts. While hazardous material responders were able to slow the leak to a fast drip they were unsuccessful at completely securing the container. A containment pool was placed under the manway area to collect the released material. Mideast Wrecking was contacted to re-rail the railcars. UTLX646672 was up righted and placed back onto its truck assemblies at 1920 hours. 400 gallons of Sodium Chlorate Solution was released from the railcar. One hundred (100) gallons impacted the asphalt roadway I ballast media and three hundred (300) gallons was collected in the containment pools. Due to the mechanical damage (train line, twisted stub sill and safety appliance) the railcar will require transfer of contents. Arrangements are currently being made to complete this process.   Cause Code: T207   ATARI: 5(5+3+0) x (4+0) = 160

column168: HDMU 423968 was reported by the outbound drayage driver oozing a white paint substance at the bottom sidewalls of this intermodal container while it was parked and staged within the intermodal parking lot. HDMU 423968 was carefully moved and isolated at the intermodal facility’s containment area. Shipper contract responders found and reported several five gallon steel pails (UN package specification 1A2/Y1.5/90/06/M4121) on a bottom pallet that were damaged when the loaded pallet of similar five gallon pails stacked atop shifted during transit. Four pails leaked from small sidewall cracks sustained from vertical crushing. All leaking pails, along with other damaged pails that did not leak, were placed into over-packs and returned inside HDMU 423968 after it was cleaned and the lading inside was properly blockEd and braced for continuing transportation (export to China).
column169: Ensure shipper uses acceptable blocking and bracing techniques and configurations that eliminate any intransit load shifts

column168: PACKAGE BROKE---CONTENTS SPILLED---CONTENTS WERE REMOVED FROM AREA AND DMP'D

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: An outbound driver reported container HDMU 213688 with a crystallized substance at the rear of this container’s chassis. HDMU 213688 was carefully moved to the intermodal facility’s containment area. BNSF and shipper contractors inspected HDMU 213688 and discovered one 50 pound bag had been punctured and was leaking product. The puncture was most likely caused by a nail protrusion from the container’s rear plywood bracing wall that was installed to secure the load. The damaged bag was placed inside an over-pack container. Four pallets of bagged product that were double stacked were removed from the rear of this container and all spillage was cleaned. The pallets that were removed and the over-pack were returned to the load. The rear bracing wall was carefully reinstalled and the rear doors of HOMU 213688 were closed. Response was concluded by 1650 hrs. CST, 3/08/07.

column58: Manway or Dome Cover; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported TILX 190003 leaking product from the manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard. TILX 190003 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard for further inspection. An initial inspection by a BNSF hazardous material responder confirmed that product had leaked down both sides of the side shell. The source appeared to be from the connection between the manway nozzle and the manway cover. All eight manway securement bolts were tool tight. The manway gasket appeared inset at the 8-9 oclock position, possibly out of position. The shipper was notified to arrange for inspection and or replacement of the manway gasket. TILX 190003 which was not leaking product remained isolated in the railyard until repairs were accomplished. In the late afternoon on 3/1/07, TILX 190003 was reported leaking product from the manway cover and also at the 75 psi safety relief valve, an indication of an overfilled condition from product expansion. The ambient temperature was 80 degrees Containment was placed under TILX 190003 to catch any drippage off the side shell. The manway lid was opened and product was noted only 1-2 inches below the manway nozzle lip. The manway gasket appeared to be in good condition. A contractor was called to facilitate off-loading of the excess product into a tanker truck. Approximately 1100 gallons of product was transferred without incident and concluded by 2310 hrs. PDT, 3/1/07. Non-contaminated spillage that was captured in the containment receptacles was also transferred into the tanker truck. Afterwards, the manway cover was closed and properly secured. A BNSF seal numbered 2156401 was applied at the manway cover. The specification stencil on the side of TILX 190003 indicated that tank qualification was accomplished in the year 2004.
column169: It was recommended to the shipper to further compensate for product expansion and the shipper will arrange to increase the product outage levels on future shipments

column168: During an outbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard, the BNSF railcar inspectors reported GATX 42126 with a fresh product stain on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately responded and reported finding 4 of 8 manway securement bolts hand tight; and the manway nozzle gasket was out of position and hanging over the lip. The responder loosened the manway securement bolts and inspected the manway gasket which was cut/split. The damaged gasket was removed and a rew manway gasket was installed. The manway cover was closed and properly secured. Spillage on the side shell was neutralized with baking soda. Product droplets that fell onto the ballast and a railroad tie under GATX 42126 were also neutralized. Response was concluded by 1855 hrs. CDT, 3/15/07.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Carteret truck pulled onto the Morrisville site with Mineral Spirits flowing from the rear of the trailer. Morrisville called it in.  Release came from tote serial # 97568. Valve handle on the bottom of the tote had been pysically removed and put on in a reverse fashion, probably by the customer so it would be easier to access while using a hose with quick connect fittings. This exposed the handle to other freight friction. When the Carteret material handler loaded another tote next to it they did not space them and rubbed the handle which caused it to open partially. I am supposing the bottom safety cap was not completely fastened and completely released sometime during transport releasing an unknown volume of material. Approximately 15-20 gallons of material was released while we responded at Morrisville. The material was contained and absorbed and cleaned up by site personel.
column169: Re-educate material handlers in checking tote prior to filling container.

column168: USCG officers were conducting random hazmat container inspection on the Horizon Lines San Juan Facility on March 7th.  One of the officers (Omar Borges) entered container HRZU450640 and was inspecting the shipment when he was overcome by fumes and taken to the hospital by emergency personnel.  The shipment was loaded with various hazardous waste products with identification numbers UN1993, UN3175, UN2927 and UN3077. the container was sealed by the USCG and the cargo was transferred into another container under the supervision of the USCG the following day.  There was no evidence of any leaking cargo from the outside or the interior of the container.  Air samplings of the container were also made but the hazmat responder indicated that there were no readings which would have caused the officer to have problems.  I phoned the NRC but was told that if there was no release then there was no report requirement.  The San Juan office made a report based on their finding under the NRC # indicated on Page #1.
column169: USCG inspectors shoud inspect with care.  It is good that they work in teams.  The second officer was able to work with the officer involved in the incident and get him to safety quickly.  Containers loaded with chemicals and are moving in a high ambient humid environment must be inspected carefully.  The high temperatures coupled with the humidity and residual odors from the packaging can cause problems during inspections.

column168: At the FAA’s request, we opened 7 packages shipped from Trans Design and discovered undeclared dangerous goods. Each package contained the following: Thirty 30 ml bottles of fingernail polish, eight 30 ml bottles of fingernail polish thinner, and 50 1 ml bottles of eye lash adhesive. There was a 5 piece shipment going to Dubai with the following tracking numbers: Master 932805759520, MI’S #s 932805759531, 932805759564, 932805759542,932805759553. The other two packages were air waybill   923805759439 going to Singapore, and 932805759510 going to Vaught, AN. The FAA was notified and seized all 7 packages.
column169: FEDEX EXPRESS WILL EMBARGO FUTURE SHIPMENTS UNTIL ISSUES ARE RESOLVED.

column168: On 20Mar07, at approximately 0955 hours, TILX 20133 in Framingham Yard, had a release of Carbon Dioxide from the Frangible Disc assembly, the tank car was stationary at the time of the incident, the Framingham Fire Dept. was called due to the loud noise being generated by the release of product from the disc failure.  Chemtrec was notified at 1049 hours 20Mar07 report number 03202007-030, the shipper BOC Gases was notified and a technician responded to check the pressure of the product, the two regulating and PRD-Valve for proper operations, no exceptions were found with the safety devices.  TILX 20133 was stationed away from the general area and allowed to vent until 2200 hours when the product auto-refrigerated.  BOC Gases technician Tom Hogan, replaced the rupture disc, his comment was disc appeared to have no defects, but was blown; he inspected the PRD-Valve and the two regulating valves and took no exception to their operation.  Tank car TILX 20133 will be inspected daily by BOC Gases personnel until Sunday, 01Apr07, and it will dispositioned to the Attleboro, MA facility.    Cause Code:  441  NARRI:  2 (5+1+0) x (3+0) = 36
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On Sunday, March 25th at 2015 hours CSX Savannah Yard Trainmaster Jay Mosley was notified that tank car UTLX 88133 (Residue: Last Contained Ammonia, Anhydrous) was emitting an odor of ammonia.  Trainmaster Mosley immediately isolated the area around the railcar and implemented the corporation's emergency response plan.  Chemtrec was notified (report number 03252007013) and the shipper, PCS Sales was informed of the release.  SWS First Response was contracted by CSX to respond and secure the railcar.  Once on site, SWS representatives found the cause of the release was due to a worn pressure relief device "O" ring. SWS attempted to remove the retainer plate from the pressure relief device, however was unsuccessful due to thread damage towards the top of the stem.  After loosening the retainer plate as much as possible they were able to rotate the worn "O" ring.  The retainer plate was then tightened back into position which secured the release.  The shipper, PCS Sales will apply for an FRA Movement Approval to forward the railcar to its nearby facility where the container will be de-pressurized.  Cause Code:  414  NARRI:  5 (4+9+0) x (2+0) = 130

SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 3 X 1 LITER METAL RECEPTACLES OF GASOLINE, CLASS 3. UN1203, AND 1 X 1 LITER METAL RECEPTACLE OF DIESEL FUEL, CLASS 3,  UN1202. DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE ON 1 RECEPTACLE CONTAINING GASOLINE, A TOTAL OF .5 OUNCES OF GASOLINE WAS LOST. column168: In the unloading process, an operator (consignee employee) was using a forklift to move 4 drums (on a pallet) from a Univar truck to the customer's facility.  As he was exiting the trailer, he caught one of the drums on the edge of the trailer.  This caused a gouge which resulted in a small leak of Acetone.  The operator immediately moved the drums to a safe area and turned the drum on its side to stop the release.  Less than 1 gal of Acetone was leaked (in a dripping pattern) between the trailer and the area where the leak was stopped.  When the operator went to clean up the leaked material, he found that it had all evaporated.
column169: Training issue.  The management of the customer site was notified of this incident so that they could retrain their employee on safe forklift operating procedures.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: Truck driver failed to adhere to necessary safety precautions when he tried to avoid a traffic light change, increasing speed and taking a turn too fast for conditions.  While attempting the turn, he lost control of the tractor-cargo tank trailer, causing the tractor and tanker to rollover. Driver was taken to the hospital, but was treated and release.  Miami-Dade Police Department cited the truck driver for careless driving.  Shipper and carrier dispatched responders to the scene at 1425P.  Miami-Dade Hazmat (fire department) as well as Police Department at the scene, estimated 10 gallons of sodium hypochlorite had been lost, but leak was not continuous (tanker had a crack in the shell near the front end top of the tanker).  Shipper and carrier drove additional, good cargo tanker to scene, and proceeded to offload sodium hypochlorite product from damaged tanker to good tanker.  Once all product removed at 2320P, both tractor and tanker involved in accident towed from the scene.  Tanker was a total lost, and tractor has damages valued at three quarters its value.  At 2340P, Miami-Dade public responders complete an inspection of scene and proceed with any final clean-up of scene.  At 0030A police open east bound side of 116 Way.  At 0130A, response is terminated and 116 Way open in all directions as well as two gas stations near scene which public responders closed for precaution.  No means available here to attach photograph of damage to cargo tanker, in future maybe online incident report can add a field for photograph attachments.
column169: Serious driver error.  Driver suspended during investigation.  Upon his return, he received a writting counseling from company regarding careless driving which included:  a) suspended from driving cargo tankers for a period of one year, and will be re-evaluated after one year, and b)must complete Liberty Mutual Decision Driving training course again.

column168: A CSX Transportation yard crew, while switching cars in Robb Ave. Yard, Lima, OH, 03/22/07 at 2255 hours, reported a cloud atop RCRX 1358.  Yardmaster M. Winthrop advised CSXT, Public Safety Coordination Center (PSCC).  Local authorities were advised.  Allen County, OH Office of Homeland Security + Emergency Management responded.  CSXT dispatched Eagle Construction and Environmental Services (ECESI), Findley, OH.  CSXT Hazardous Materials Field Services Manager T.J. Mannas arrived at 0155, 03/23/07.  Local authorities had recently departed as ECESI had successfully stopped the leak.  T.J. Mannas inspected RCRX 1358 with ECESI personnel and advised they tightened four of four securement bolts for the blind closure flange of the air line.  T.J. Mannas contacted Mr. Russ Decker, CEM Director, Allen County, OH Office of Homeland Security + Emergency Management on 3/23/07.  Mr. Decker advised he ordered a "voluntary evacuation" of 13 residences following the guidelines of the U.S. DOT ERG for Hydrochloric Acid.  Mr. Decker further advised only nine of the thirteen residences were occupied at the time of the evacuation.  T.J. Mannas contacted Zaclon, Inc., Cleveland, OH personnel, Messrs Jon Hall and John Curry to discuss the events surrounding RCRX 1358.  They advised that they would handle for corrective action with their personnel.  Cause Code:  321  NARRI:  5 (4+5+0) X (2+4) = 270
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The TILX 320020 was located on the TASD RIP track in the TASD interchange where I discovered the leak. coming from the bottom outlet valve at 0930. column169: All bottom outlet valves should be inspected throughly before departure from any facility, industry etc. Special attention should be take by all car owners or any repair facility on BOV's when they are in the shop for any type of repairs. column168: PRODUCT THAT WAS BEING TRANPOSRTED TO ROSS INCINERATION, IN GRANFTON, OH BEGAN TO HAVE A CHEMICAL REACTION WHILE IN TRANSIT.  UNIT BEGAN TO HEAT UP AND BUILD PRESSURE WITHIN THE TANK.  AT APPROXIMATELY 35 LBS OF PRESSURE THE PRESSURE RELEIF OPENED AND ALLOWED VAPOR TO ESCAPE THE TRAILER, AT APPROXIMATELY 37 LBS OF PRESURE AND BETWEEN 178 AND 200 DEG, THE FUSIBLE CAP RELEASED AND ALSO BEGAN TO VENT THE TRAILER TO THE ATMOSPHERE.    J.J.'S TRUCK STOP WAS CLOSED FOR 5 DAYS.  THERE WERE A FEW PEOPLE FROM HOMES ABOUT A MILE OR TWO AWAY THAT HAD BEEN EVACUATED AS A PRECAUSTION THE DEAY OF THE RELEASE.  THEY WERE ALLOWED BACK IN THEIR HOMES THAT NIGHT.

Driver was venting off approximately three (3) pounds of hydrochloric acid solution pressure from our trailer into a scrubber designed for that purpose when the bag inside the scrubber broke, releasing a small cloud of hydrochloric acid vapors.
column169: We feel that the failure was due in part to the driver venting off too fast and also the design of the scrubber we do not feel was adequate.    Consequently, we have discontinued the use of that scrubber, will cut it up and dispose of it properly and clean up the area around the drum to the satisfaction of the Louisana Department of Environmental Quality.  In addition, we will be using the scrubber at our shipper's facility to bleed off any remaining pressure in our trailers and have talked with our drivers about the proper use of the scrubber.

column169: SUGGESTION FIND A BETTER WAY TO SECURE DRUMS TO PALLET, LIMITING POSSIBLITY OF THE DRUMS TO SLIDE FROM SIDE TO SIDE.  KEEPING THE DRUMS BETTER SECURE.

column168: Driver was traveling on private dirt/gravel road approaching a blind curve.  Driver manuevered vehicle to right edge of roadway to avoid possible on-coming traffic in blind curve.  Roadway was soft and muddy due to recent heavy rain.  Driver lost control of truck on soft shoulder.  Driver attempted to stir back to center of roadway, but trailer slid off roadway on right side and overturned gently due to load surge. Driver exited cab and contacted company. There was no release from cargo tank, no injuries to driver. Product was transferred to another cargo tank truck and wrecker service crews uprighted vehicle and towed to repair facilities.
column169: Driver was traveling too fast and too close to the right shoulder for weather and road conditions.     More training on appropriate speed for weather and road conditions.  Emphasize safe driving techniques for offroad travel and how to appropriately respond to a tire dropping off roadway.

column168: Driver noticed oncoming vehicle on 2 lane county road crossing center line headed toward him.  Tank truck driver moved right to fog line to try to avoid a head-on collision and not roll the truck in the ditch.  Car impacted the truck on the left side tearing rear axle and suspension out from under the truck causing our vehicle to roll onto its side.  Driver immediately called emergency response, took flashlight to inspect cargo tank,noticed cargo tank was intact, compartment #2 & #3 domelids were dry, #1 domelid small leak.  Immediately diked ditch with spill pads, placed 5 gallon bucket under dripping dome lid seal.  Company reponders showed up to scene and pumped out tipped over tank truck, elimating any additional release.  Tow truck uprighted truck, towed to shop, Environmental Services remained on scene to collect and monitor product that escaped drivers dike.
column169: Our annual hazwoper driving training & review was conducted on Saturday March 10th, 2007 Driver took appropriate action for the situation of an on-coming car crossing the center line to avoid a head-on collision that would have entailed the loss of life when he did not have the time to manuevor in any other direction.  If the truck had not been impacted it would not have tipped on its side.

column168: HALLIBURTON ENERGY SERVICE EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING AN F700 BODY LOAD STAKE BED TRUCK ON WYOMING STATE HIGHWAY 59 SOUTH.  AROUND 7:00AM, THE EMPLOYEE ATTEMPTED TO TURN ONTO WYOMING STATE HIGHWAY 450 EAST.  THE TRUCK HAD TWO FULL 330 GALLON TOTES, ONE WITH MO-85M AND THE OTHER WITH MO-86M, AND ABOUT 600LBS OF MO-4 BREAKER.  THE TRUCK ENTERED THE TURN TOO FAST, AND THE SHIFTING OF THE LIQUID IN THE TOTES CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO TURN OVER ON IT'S SIDE THAT HIT THE GROUND.  ALL CONTENTS OF BOTH TOTES WERE LOST IN ABOUT 15MIN OR LESS DUE TO THE DAMAGE.  THE LIQUID RAN OUT ONTO THE ROAD AND INTO THE BAR DITCH.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED AT THE LOCAL HOSPITAL IN GILLETTE WITH NO INJURIES.    ANCHOR ENVIRONMENTAL PERFORMED CLEANUP AT THE SITE FOR HALLIBURTON ENERGY SERVICES.  SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL.  THE TOP 2-3" OF SOIL WAS SCRAPED AND REMOVED. PH OF SOIL WAS TESTED TO NEUTRAL.
column169: EMPLOYEE WAS TRAVELLING TOO FAST INTO THE TURN, AND WAS SHIFTING GEARS AS HE WAS TURNING.  DRIVERS OF VEHICLES HANDLING LOADS WHICH CAN SHIFT IN TANKS WILL BE RE-INSTRUCTED OF THE NECESSITY TO REDUCE SPEED PRIOR TO ENTERING A TURN OF SUCH MAGNITUDE, AND NOT TO SHIFT GEARS WHILE TURNING, OR IN AN INTERSECTION.

column168: During routine shipment of 2 - 10 cubic yard lugger boxes of the previously mentioned waste, the driver approached the intersection of Wales Road and Oregon Road. As he came to the intersection, the light turned yellow and he applied the brakes hard. In doing so, the force of the stop caused material from the rear box to cascade over the top and spill on to the roadway. The driver remained stopped and called PSC dispatch for help. Northwood police and fire were on the site within 10 minutes and diverted traffic. The spill was contained to the the immediate area around the vehicle. No waterways or drains were affected.    Within 20 minutes of the incident, PSC responded and applied absorbents to the area and proceeded to clean up the roadway. All spilled material and absobents were placed back into the container from which the material originally spilled. The containers were then transported back to the generator for proper fixation.
column169: All boxes at the generators site will be inspected for free liquids. If free liquids are found, the generator will need to pump them or absorb them to prevent reoccurance.

column168: The Intercoastal Transport Company driver was at the Town of La Plata's Well Site #10 to deliver an IBC of the sodium hypochlorite solution.  During the unloading of the sodium hypochlorite solution, the IBC cracked circumferentially at approximately the 305 gallon mark around half of the circumference of the IBC and then diagonally 3/4 of the way down the body of the IBC.  Approximately 165 gallons was transferred into an on site open top storage container.  After the product was completely unloaded from the IBC, the driver called the office to report the incident.  I left immediately and arrived on the scene at 09:45 hours.  The well house is situated on top of a slight hill and the hypochlorite had concentrated at the bottom of the hill near the bend in the gravel driveway.  I spread a dry dechlorinating product to neutralize the chlorine, and then contacted the National Response Center and Maryland Environmental Service's main office.  Maryland Environmental Service is contracted by the Town of La Plata to operate the Town's water and wastewater facilities.  The Town sent an equipment operator from the Public Works Department to the site with a backhoe to mix the soil with the dechlorinating product.  I continued to apply the dechlorinating product until the area did not register for residual chlorine.
column169: The first thing Intercoastal Trading Inc did to prevent a recurrence was to immediately suspend the shipping of any IBC over five years old.  The IBC which failed was over seven years old and had been in hypochlorite solution service.   The five year limit was a conservative number based on a projected IBC lifespan of ten to fifteen years.  The only IBC Intercoastal Trading Inc uses is the heavy weight ultratainer as manufactured by Snyder Industries Inc of Lincoln, Nebraska.  This IBC is considered by some to be the most durable IBC available.  When this IBC was manufactured, it had a substantial pressure rating of 428 KPa.  Historically we have found the performance of the Snyder Ultratainer to be extremely good especially compared to other manufacturer’s IBC’s.  We feel that the hazards and risks associated with the transportation of hazardous materials are minimized in the Snyder Ultratainer IBC’s.

column168: It was reported that tank car, GATX 71775, load Flammable Liquid, NOS (Crude Sulfate Turpentine) was leaking while in a CSX Transportation train, Q21613 stopped at New Boston, MI, MP CC95.8 near Eureka Road. The local police department was notified arid CSXT’s hazardous materials department responded an emergency response contractor to inspect and repair the car. The shipper, Weyerhaeuser Co LTD, was notified via CHEMTREC (report #03132007096). The contractor advised that when they arrived they did not see any sign of any free product release from the car. They found that the packing gland nut was loose on the top operating rod for the bottom outlet valve allowing vapors to escape. They tightened the packing gland nut and the vapors/odors stopped. column168: Univar driver, David Mumford, at a stop just prior to the delivery where the incident ocurred, had secured three 55-gal drums against the right sidewall of his trailer near the rear door and a pallet of bags ahead of the drums by approx. 20ft. He placed a pallet jack under the pallet of bags and "pumped" the handle a few times to bring pressure against the jack and pallet, thus expecting the jack to not move during transit. When he pulled into the customer site, there were some uneven surfaces and turns that caused some bumping of his trailer thus loosening the pallet jack hydraulic handle and allowing it to roll unobstructed into the drum of N-Propyl Alcohol. It made a large gash a few inches off the bottom of the drum which allowed the product to completely empty in a short amount of time.    When David proceeded to the back of the trailer, he smelled the product and upon opening the door and seeing the liquid, immediately went to his trailer spill kit and pulled the contents out to protect a storm drain and keep as much of the product contained as he could. At the same time the truck was opened, the customer was present and he contacted the Midvale Fire Dept. who responded and took over managing the spill.    David then contacted his Supervisor, Tim Daw who in turn notified his Manager, Bob Sollesvik who directed Tim to travel to the site and gather all pertinate information and advise status of the incident. Operations Manager Bob Sollesvik was in route on a travel trip to another satellite branch in S.E. Idaho but was able to contact Univar's environmental response company, ET Technologies to stand by for respone in the event there needed to be a storm drain clean up.    The Salt Lake County Health Department arrived on the scene to inspect and monitor the drain and once the cleanup was completed, advised that the storm drain was properly protected and there was not a need for a cleanup team to come to the site.    David Mumford and Tim Daw completed the cleanup of the absorbent material once the Midvale FD gave the ok to enter the spill scene. David and Tim swept up all absorbent material (absorbent pads & soda ash) into an 85gal poly recovery drum, properly labeled it then transported it to the Univar facility in Salt Lake City for proper processing. As the product was solvent in nature, all liquid was soaked up with spill pads and did not leave residue in the trailer that could potentially continue to leak in transit. For precautionary measures, the trailer was unloaded at the Univar Salt Lake City facility and then was taken to a wash rack for cleaning.
column169: Upon review of the incident, it was determined that the driver had not had "official" load securement training. However, the week prior during a review of a load he was to take, he had communicated to his manager that all material handling devices, such as pallet jacks, drum dollies and hand carts must be secured to either the side walls of the trailer or under a pallet with ratchet straps to prevent movement within the trailer during transit. Driver has received his "official" load securement training and management has noted as a corrective action item on the Univar Incident Investigation Report, that all new hire drivers will not be allowed to take a solo load until they have completed all company mandated driver training.

3/22/07; at approximately 2:50PM, CSXT road crew of Q434-2 was moving past car and noted NATX 37164, load Methanol, leaking from the top of the car.  Car was not moving.  Further inspection by CR's Mechanical Superintendent R. Caparelli found the liquid valve was not completely closed.  Valve closed and leaked secured.  Further inspection by CR's A. Richter, Mgr. Risk, and REACT's R. Gould, found the closure plug for said valve was cross-threaded, and holding onto valve threads by merely 2-3 threads at the bottom of the plug.      Closure plug was removed, noting remenants of teflon-like material at various locations on the interior threads of the valve where the plug is applied.  Additionally, numerous flakes of a teflon-like material were surrounding the closed ball valve, prohibiting the valve from proper closure.    The foreign material was cleaned from the threads and ball, a liquid pipe dope was applied to the closure plug threads, allowing the plug to be adequately secured for transportation to original destination.    Additional note: all six manway cover securement bolts were not totally tool tight.  Made secure prior to transportation.

column168: Employees were in the process of receiving #2 diesel fuel from an oil tanker and connected the unloading hose to the fill line for a tank that was out-of-service.  The tank had been cleaned and the piping disconnected.  Approximately 600 gallons of oil spilled from the tank discharge line connection onto the ground.        There were two tanks used for diesel storage on sites T8 and T9.  Both had been cleaned and degassed. Tank 9 was ready for service and was to be used to store fuel for Ritchie 3(CTG).  Tank 8 had been out service for ten years. Employees checked the drawing and concluded that tank 9 was lined up for service. There were no identifiable markings or tags on the fill lines for either tank. Only one of the fill lines had a hose connector for unloading fuel and the operators connected the tanker to that line and began off loading.  When they went to check the receiving tank, they noticed oil running out of tank 8.        US Environmental was contacted to respond to the oil spill.
column169: The fill lines to tanks 8 and 9 have been properly labeled.  The fill valve for tank 8 has been removed and the line capped. The oil that was inadvertently pumped into tank 8 has been removed and the tank cleaned to prevent this from happening again.

column168: A BNSF train crew reported 'dust' blowing off entrained gondolas. This multiple railcar shipment consisting of twenty gondolas was immediately setout of this train at Wishram, WA. The shipper was notified of this event and arranged for a contractor familiar with these types of shipments to inspect the 20 railcars and initiate appropriate securement corrections. This shipment was inspected the morning of 4/02/07. The contractor reported that the commodity inside the gondolas appeared intact. A small amount of binder cracking was noted at the commodity end slopes inside the gondolas. The contractor was also of the opinion that this binder cracking was insufficient to result in the release of commodity 'dust' during train movement and normal wind conditions. The shipper's contractor resprayed the commodity inside the gondolas with another coating of binder to prohibit any further 'dust' erosions. During this binder respray, it was noted that the ambient high winds were between 15 and 25 mph and no blow off of this commodity inside the gondolas was observed. After all 20 gondolas were resprayed, this shipment was released to proceed to its destination and it arrived at that destination without further incident.
column169: BNSF and the shipper are working towards testing and adding protective coverings (tarpaulins) on future gondola shipments.

column168: on 3/17/07 at 0900 TASD crew were dragging a cut of loaded coal cars on the Old Dump Lead at the AL State Docks McDuffie Island Coal Handling Facility when TASD Locomotive's 771 and 772 derailed along with two loaded coal cars causing the fuel tank to rupture on locomotive 771, discharging 850 gallons of bio diesel fuel between the Old Dump Lead and the Middle Loop track. The TASD yardmaster notified the AL. State Docks Protection Department and the Mobile Fire department was dispatched to the scene. United States Enviromental was contacted and arrived on the scence at 1000 along with an Al. Department Enviromental Management representative. McDuffie Island employees assisted in containment of spill using oil dry. In house clean-up using backhoes was used to remove contaminated dirt and coal which was set to the roadside clear of the Old Dump Lead. United States Enviromental Services arrived on 3/19/07 at 0830 with equipment and four roll on boxes and removed contaminated dirt and coal to dispose at the Macland Disposal Center located in Moss Point Mississippi.

column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. LIDS AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TO PREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING, RELEASING THE LIQUID. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PAGKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. column168: The driver was returning to his terminal after having unloaded his product.  While conducting an inspection of his vehicle after a rest stop, driver noticed a leak coming from the on-board pump. A bucket was placed underneath the drip to collect free product. Under Quality Distribution Claim Number 17848, an environmental contractor was dispatched to assess the situation and remediate the release. It was determined that residual product had been released through the pump. The spill was neutralized and the pump was determined to be empty. The "crash box" area housing the pump was outfitted with chemical absorbent pads as a precautionary measure to allow the driver to return to his home terminal. The driver returned to his home terminal without incident.

column62: Corrosion - Exterior; Defective Component or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew reported UTLX 130339 releasing product from the top fitting area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 130339 and reported no active leaks detected when this tank car was standing still. The leak source appeared to be emanating from the liquid line area. The four flange bolts and nuts atop the liquid line were corroded which prevented a tool tight condition. A BNSF contractor replaced the four corroded bolts and nuts; and tightened down the flange connection. After this securement was completed, the contractor's applied sodium bicarbonate to neutralize the spillage at the fitting and side shell area of UTLX 130339. The neutralized spillage was then water washed. The small amount of product that impacted the ground was also neutralized. Response was concluded by 1940 hrs. PDT, 3/16/07.

column168: Transportation unit was on site to deliver fuel. As the driver was positioning the transportation unit for off loading the fuel, the driver turned too soon not allowing adequate space between the trailer and a metal pole protecting the fuel pump. The resulting impact caused a breach in the trailer resulting in the release of 1800 gallons of unleaded gasoline.     The resulting release caused initial contamination in and around the fueling station. Due to the location of the fueling area (up gradient), the fuel traveled down gradient from the release point and caused off site contamination to an adjacent business. Currently, Flying J Transportation, LLC is assessing the environmental damage to the site and performing site remediation and restoration activities.
column169: Flying J Transportation drivers will be retrained on turning radius required for proper clearance of obstacles. Drivers will be reminded to keep constant visual of trailer while turning to avoid a potential collision (use of driver and passenger side mirrors).

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery at Exxon Mobil Chemical Company, product was offloaded into the wrong tank, which caused the tank to overflow.  The technical name for the products released are Varsol 1 Fluid, and Solvent Blend 19299, both products are shipped as petroleum distillates, n.o.s.  According to the Material Safety Data Sheets, the products contain the following ingredients:Varsol 1 Fluid contains:Stoddard Solvent, CAS# 8052-41-3, 100%, Component contains Pseudocumene (1,2,4-Trimethylbenzene), CAS# 95-63-6, 4%. 1,2,4-Trimethylbenzene, CAS# 95-63-6, is listed under section 313 of SARA Title III List of Lists.  The ingredient is not listed under section 304 of CERCLA with a reportable quantity.  Solvent Blend 19299 - Light aliphatic solvent naphtha (petroleum), CAS# 64742-89-8 contains: Heptane, all isomers, CAS# 142-82-5, 30-100%,Octanes, all isomers, CAS# Mixture,   1-15%, Methylcyclohexane, CAS# 108-87-2, <10%, Toluene, CAS# 108-88-3, 5%.  Toluene, CAS# 108-88-3, is listed under section 313 of SARA Title III List of Lists.  The ingredient is also listed under section 304 of CERCLA with a reportable quantity of 1,000 pounds.    Approximately 1,000 gallons of petroleum distillates, n.o.s. were released.  Product was contained within the earthen dike which surrounds the storage tank.  Product did not migrate beyond the diked area, or enter into any storm drains or waters of the state.  Inland Waters of Ohio of Cleveland, Ohio was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Inland Waters of Ohio proceeded to use a vacuum truck to recover the free product and rain water from within the diked area.  Approximately 1,800 gallons of contaminated water were recovered.  Inland Waters of Ohio also applied absorbent blankets around the storage tank to catch any residual product, and placed absorbent pillows by the shutoff valve, which leads to the oil/water separator on the property.  Upon inspection of the oil/water separator, it was determined that the product did not enter the system or travel to the oil/water separator.  Bart Ray of the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency was on scene during cleanup activity, and authorized cleanup actions and containment.  Inland Waters of Ohio continued to monitor the site, and swap out existing absorbent blankets and pillows until no further residual product remained.  Contaminated absorbent material was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum.  Disposal was coordinated direct by Inland Waters of Ohio in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental and occurred due to an overflow from the storage tank while offloading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Tandet Group, Inc. will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: As the USL DSR was unloading a purchase trailer, he discovered a leak coming from the bottom side of a pallet. Upon inspection, we discovered a box had been punctured. We removed the pallet from the trailer, unwrapped and seperated the boxes to find the leaker. The one damaged package had a punctured can slightly leaking with a slow drip. No pictures were taken of the damaged product. We   re-stacked the remaining good boxes back on the pallet and sent the pallet on to the next service center. It looks like the box had been leaking for the entire transportation trip from origin to our facility. There was cardboard and wooden sheets urder the pallet which helped to slow the spread and absorb the liquid. Cleanup was very little as the liquid did not spread far.
column169: The only suggestion in this scenario is to double check the condition of liquid freight upon loading. There was sufficient dunnage used under the pallet, but not on all five other sides.

column168: On March 30, 2007, at approximately 1338 hours, a railway tankcar ACFX 79107, loaded with Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., flammable, UN1993 PG III, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Baton Rouge Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the BOV and BOV cap. The cap was loose, the valve was open 4 turns and the gasket was bad. The shipper representative responded to the site, replaced the gasket, closed the valve, tightened the cap and cleaned up the spill.  There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.        CODE: 155  NARRI: 5(5+1+0)x(2+0)=60
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed. A pull-away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

column168: When stopping for a railroad crossing on Beltline Drive and then taking off the material inside the tank trailer sloshed to the rear of the tanker rupturing the rupture disk. The driver noticed the material as it sloshed out of the top of the tanker and pulled off the shoulder of the road after making the turn onto Ecology Lane. The driver explained that the material (about a gallon ) had dripped from the drip tubes of the tanker. In speaking with a witness that was behind the driver he estimated the loss to be between 7 and 12 gallons during stopping and taking off. Univar sent an employee to the sceen to clean up the spillage into 5 gallon buckets and to make repairs to the tank truck so that it could be off loaded at the customer utilizing the tractor pump vs. air pad. The material was also cleaned off the edge of the road using absorbent material, collected into a 55 gallon open head container (200 pounds) and sent for disposal as Non RECRA Waste. The tank trailer was then taken to the shop for perminate repairs to the rupture disk area.
column169: Tank trailer has been fitted with a pressure relief valve in place of the rupture disk to prevent recurrance.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS BEING UNLOADED AT A GEORGIA PACIFIC PLANT AT 1429 LUFKIN AVE., LUFKIN TX, BY PLANT PERSONNEL.  A PLANT OPERATOR AWOKE THE DRIVER AND GAVE HIM SIGNED BILLS FOR THE PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER REMAINED IN HIS CAB AS PER INSTRUCTIONS STARTED HIS VEHICLE AND PULLED AWAY.  DOING THIS HE PULLED THE HOSE, THAT WAS STILL ATTACHED TO HIS TRAILER LOOSE & BROKE THE CONNECTION.  DRIVER CONTINUED FROM THE PLANT (APPROX 200YDS) ACROSS LUFKIN AVE. WHERE HE STOPPED AFTER SEEING LIQUID SPILL FROM THE REAR OF HIS VEHICLE.  DRIVER CLOSED HIS VALVES STOPPING THE LEAK.  G.P. PERSONNEL TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  LUFKIN FIRE DEPT. CLOSED THE ROAD & BEGAN A CONTAINMENT. UPON MY ARRIVAL I CALLED FOR GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES-HOUSTON TEXAS TO TAKE CONTROL OF CLEANUP.  I WILL ATTACH INVOICES TO SHOW THEIR ACTIONS TAKEN.  LUFKIN FIRE DEPT. & STUART DEPT.  REMAINED ON THE SCENE UNTIL CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED.  TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY INVESTIGATOR ON SCENE.
column169: THE PLANT MANAGER FOR GEORGIA PACIFIC-LUFKIN, THE OWNER OF H.O.T TRANSPORT AND I MET AFTER THIS INCIDENT.  WE DID COME UP WITH A POSSIBLE SOLUTION.  G.P. WOULD INSTALL LARGE SIGNS TO PLACE IN FRONT OF THE TRUCKS PREVENTING THEM FROM BEING MOVED.  THE SIGNS WOULD ONLY BE MOVED BY PLANT OPERATORS WHEN VEHICLES ARE READY TO LEAVE THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  ALSO THE DRIVERS WOULD BE ALLOWED TO GET OUT OF THEIR VEHICLES TO CHECK VEHICLE CONDITION BEFORE MOVING.  BOTH DRIVER AND PLANT OPERATOR MUST BE AWARE OF THE SAFETY CONDITION OF THE VEHICLE BEFORE IT IS MOVED.  NO SHORTCUTS ALLOWED.

column168: The Lake City Police Department investigated a report from the Goodhue County Sherriff’s Department that a southbound train was leaking a substance that smelled like ammonia. The officer confirmed the chemical leak as the train passed by and advised his dispatcher to call the railroad. The Canadian Pacific Railway & Iowa, Chicago and Eastern Railroad were notified that the IC&E MSPKC-17 train, traveling south on the Canadian Pacific Railway’s River Subdivision Mainline Track, did indeed have a chemical leak. The train was stopped south of Lake City, MN and the crew was evacuated. Residents in the immediate area were evacuated and the Emergency Operations Center (EOC) was activated. As more information from the scene was relayed, forces were dispatched including local fire, emergency management, ambulance, law, IC&E Emergency Responders, CP Emergency Responders, MN Regional Haz-Mat Responders, MN State Responders and contract Haz-Mat responders. The contracted Haz-Mat team was able to seal the anhydrous ammonia tank car’s leak, which was found to be coming from the pressure relief valve, with an Emergency Response “Midland B” Capping Kit. After the leak had been sealed and the area determined to be safe the evacuation was lifted and the area cleared. Tank Car GATX 58261 was set out at the adjacent siding for trans-loading, investigation and repairs. Tran-loading of the remaining product was completed March 20, 2007 at 1400 hours. Investigation during the teardown process of the car’s relief valve revealed a complete fracture of the valve stem which adjusts and retains the relief pressure valve. In addition, the relieve valve’s spring, retainer and nuts were observed in the bottom of the car. A new complete certified pressure relief valve was installed on site by Rescar, who was contracted by CF Industries Inc.

column168: At 1435hrs on 3-12-07, the Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by Manager Train Operations and advised that covered hopper UNPX 120386 had leaked product onto the ground at the Englewood Yard Hump as it was being pulled to the top of the hump.     Upon arrival and inspection of the area, the Mgr noted product contained between the gauge of the rail on the hump lead from the east end of the Group 7 retarder to the top of the hump; approximately 1000 feet.     Inspection of the car by mechanical personnel revealed that AB compartment which contained approximately 50,000 pounds of product to be empty. The dump door was open, and there were rolling marks on both sides of the dump door operating mechanism.     Inspection of the Group 7 retarder by track, operating, and mechanical personnel revealed a low spot in the track creating insufficient clearance. As the car was being pulled through the retarder, the dump door operating rod caught on the retarder skates causing the dump door to roll open as the car was being pulled.     After determining cause of the release, track maintenance personnel were called in to make necessary repairs to the track. Clean-up personnel were called in to vacuum and recover the product. All product was placed on plastic and covered until proper disposal arrangements could be made.     On 3-13-07, the product was loaded into dump trucks and disposed of appropriately.   Additionally, due to electrical circuit problems created from the product. The track from the top of the hump to the beginning of the Group 7 retarder was power washed. There were no reported injuries, drains or waterways impacted by this release.

column168: THE VEHICLE, PULLING A FUEL TANKER AND PUP TANKER TRAILER, WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON U.S. HWY 281, APPROACHING THE RIGHT HAND CURVE ONTO THE 281 BYPASS. AS THE VEHICLE ROUNDED THE CURVE, IT APPEARS THE PUP CAME UNHOOKED FROM THE LEAD TRAILER. THE PUP THEN STRUCK AND PUNCTURED THE CENTER AND REAR COMPARTMENTS OF THE LEAD TRAILER. CUASING THE VEHICLE TO ROLL OVER RELEASING DIESEL FUEL ONTO THE ROADWAY AND INTO A SLOUGH ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE BY-PASS. THE PUP TRAVELED INTO SOUTH DITCH AND CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE. NO FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE PUP TRAILER. HAZMAT AND ENVIROMENTAL TEAMS WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SITE. A GRAVEL BERM WAS CONSTRUCTED AROUND THE TANK TO CONTAIN THE SPILL ON THE ROADWAY, AND A WATER BOOM WAS INSTALLED IN THE SLOUGH TO PREVENT THE FUEL FROM SPREADING SOUTH. EXCAVATION OF SOIL AND VEGETATION TOOK PLACE OVER THE NEXT TWO WEEKS.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THIS ACCIDENT CANNOT BE CONCLUSIVELY DETERMINED, SO ANY SUGGESTIONS FOR IMPROVING OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES OR PACKAGING WOULD BE BASED ON SPECULATION. HOWEVER,IT IS CLEAR THAT THE PACKAGE AND ITS SAFETY DEVICES PERFORMED AS INTEDED AND DID NOT FAIL; YIELDING ONLY TO A PUNCTURE THAT THE MC-306 WAS NOT DESIGNED TO WITHSTAND. WE WILL CONTINUE THE PROGRAMS WE HAVE IN PLACE INCLUDING; SAFETY MEETINGS, DRIVER TRAINING, VEHICLE AND CARGO TANK MAINTENANCE AND RESPONSE PLANS.

column14: ST RT 22 WEST BD EXIT TO I-99
column168: On March 28, 2007 Aibright Oil, Inc. had a tractor trailer that had loaded fuel in Altoona, Pa then traveling state route 22 west bound exit ramp to 199 lost control and rolled one time. I have ask driver of incident and he does not recall what happened. Trooper Benton was on scene along with the county of Blair emergency services hazmat team and Sugar Run Spills. Our insurance company was contacted and sent consultants from Pittsburgh, Pa to oversee clean up.  There was a crack approximately 10 inches on passenger side top front of tanker and double bulk heads had failed releasing product slowly from fittings between bulk heads. These were plugged to keep product from exiting tanker. Blair County Oil had a tanker transfer product from tanker involved in accident to their tanker. The use of absorbent materials were used to contain the release along with pads and booms including small dam to contain release. Everyone involved worked diligently to keep product contamination to the environment at a minimum.  * Pictures are attached.
column169: All drivers that are employed by Albright Oil, Inc have been trained of our driving policies and procedures. We do everything that is possible to make sure that drivers operate under the conditions of all policies pertaining to safety guidelines set forth by our company. I have addressed these issues again since the accident and will continue to do so.  As far as recommendations for improvement to the Hazardous Materials Transportation Industry beyond Albright Oil, Inc. Everyone in our Industry wants what anybody would want and that is to prosper and provide for their families to the best of their abilities. This was difficult enough prior to our nations loss on 9/11. You have to have your mind on the task at hand while involved with hazardous material more today then prior to 9/11 because of outside threats. The security plans in place by our company are a must so that we can protect our employees and our nation.  It is now that anyone dealing with hazardous materials has to be held at a higher standard and have even more on their minds when responsible for their cargo. I am not saying this is the reason for our companies accident but that our way of performing our duties as part of the hazmat transportation industry has changed and will continue to change from this point on.
