column168: FILE-07-40 DOT & OMC        SHIPPER-ENVIREN SVCS INC.     AWB#- BGM 20650052850 FMS     ON 03/23/2007 AT 1210 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE BUSINESS RECEIVING LOCATION THAT THEY HAD JUST RECEIVED A LEAKING MERCURY SHIPMENT. SOMEONE PHONED THIS TO THE DHL HAZMAT HOTL1NE. AT 1219 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE   CONTACTED THE DHL EXPRESS LAKE MARY STATION, LOCATED AT 600 TECHNOLOGY PARK, SUITE 108, LAKE MARY, FL 32746. DAREM FROM THE DHL EXPRESS LAKE MARY STATION REPORTED THAT THEY HAD A MERCURY SPILL IN A DELIVERY VAN AND AT THE RECEIVER LOCATION. THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM. 3 TEAMS WERE DISPATCHED, 1 AT THE STATION, 1 AT THE DELIVERY VAN, AND 1 AT THE RECEIVER LOCATION. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE STATION, NO EVIDENCE OF LEAK WAS FOUND. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DELIVERY VAN, THE SPILL TEAM BEGAN MONITRING THE AREA AND PROPER CLEAN UP. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE RECEIVER LOCATION, THE SPILL TEAM WAS CLEANING UP THE VISIBLE MERCURY WHILE AWAITING FOR THE EQUIPMENT TO FURTHER MONITOR THE CONTAMINATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING A STOKES-MCCLOUD 276-11 THERMOMETER WITH MERCURY LEFT INSIDE OF THE GAUGE. DUE TO MERCURY BEING LEFT INSIDE OF THE GAUGE AND NOT PROPERLY PREPARED FOR TRANSPORTATION, A TOTAL OF .8 LBS OF THE MERCURY WAS LOST. .3 LB FROM THE VAN SITE AND .5 LB FROM THE RECEIVER LOCATION. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE DHL EXPRESS LAKE MARY STATION VIA TRUCK # 3241. A METER TEST WAS DONE ON 03/24/2007 AT   THE RECEIVING LOCATION AND HAD A READING OF 0.0.     THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.     CLEAR OF SCENE: 03/24/2007.
WHILE UNLOADING, DISCOVERED SKID SHIFTED IN TRANSIT PUSHING 40Z. OUT THE CAP OF ONE PAIL. MINIMAL SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS RECOUPED AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: Car Foreman, reported Tank car ACFX 82375 was leaking product from the bottom outlet valve on Track 504 in the Livonia Yard, Livonia, LA, with no waterways affected and no injuries or exposures reported. further stated the tank car was still slowly dripping product and absorbents and buckets had been placed to contain the release. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and stated he would contact the reporting party. Phalen, Point Coupee Parish was notified. All required State notifications were also completed. At 04:06 PM, Robinson advised he conferred with who stated the leakage was being released at a rate of one drop per thirty seconds. further stated containment would be maintained under the leak overnight with no expected excavation required and that he would respond in the morning on 03/02/07 to initiate final remediation. At 05:05 PM, Robinson advised he conferred with  Louisiana State Police,  Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality, and Shipper, who agreed on the previously proposed corrective actions.  On 03/02/2007 at 12:46 PM,  advised that both compartments of ACFX 82375 were dripping product. The source of the leak was the same on both compartments, between the belly of the tank and the flange of the bottom outlet chamber. After conferring with representatives of the car manufacturer it was learned that this is a metal to metal fitting secured with rivets and that no field repair options were available. Plans were made for a transload operation utilizing cargo tank trucks.  On 03/06/2007 at 06:30 AM, advised that the first cargo tank truck was on scene and transloading operations would be taking place throughout the day. At 09:00 PM, he advised that the transloading operation into cargo tank trucks has been completed.

column168: Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, Union Pacific Railroad, Tucson Arizona, received a report from the Union Pacific Mechanical repair track, that residue tank car UTLX 93205 had caught fire and was burning in the area of the protective housing. Two railroad employees were making repairs to a safety railing with a flame torch, when the fire started. There were no injuries and all employees were cleared of the area. The Tucson Fire Department responded to the fire, and along with they set up and started applying fogged water to the buring area. Entry to the top of the car was made by and the fire department. Upon lifting the lid to the protective housing, they observed a fire to be present. After extinguishing the fire and allowing time for the area to cool down, and the fire department started their investigation to determine the origin or cause of the fire. The investigation revealed that the gauging device’s protective housing was not threaded tightly according to specifications. After removing the cover, it was observed that the packing gland nut to the gauging tube was loose and not secured as required. The loose packing gland nut which was determined to have caused the vapor leak. Coupled with the gauging device housing cover not properly securied, allowed the vapor to build up within the protective housing, which in turn fueled the fire. checked all valves and fittings for proper securement and found that the two threaded plugs to the liquid line and the plug to the vapor line, were not in a wrench tight condition. These exceptions were corrected and not related to the fire. For safety reasons Mr Johnson contacted the car owner and had the car moved to an owner shop for a complete inspection of all valves and fittings for fire damage.
column169: Shipper to confer with their customers on proper securment of valves and fittings before transportation.

column168: Manager of Yard Operations, Phoenix, Arizona reported product released from the bottom outlet valve of Tankcar UTLX 200845. further advised there were no waterway or drains affected and there were no injuries nor exposures. Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and advised a contractor, ERI was en route to remediate.  reported that ERI (Contractor) found that the handle to the bottom outlet valve wasn’t in the total closed position and the two inch bottom outlet cap threads were cross threaded and allowed product to bypass the cap. The leak was slowed to a random drip. Arrangements were made with the shipper and Union Pacific Operations Phoenix to move the car a short distance to final destation, where the car could be off-loaded. Shipper is to make arrangements for home shop of the car and movement approval from the FRA (if required.)

At l83Ohrs on 3-20-07,  Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Yard Clerk, reported an unknown amount of a dark colored liquid leaking from a loaded covered hopper car. Hopper car ICCX 81050 was located on track 5, in the Freeport train yard at Mile Post 15.42 of the Freeport Industrial Lead. advised there were no drains, waterways affected nor reported injuries resulting from this release. Upon being notified, responded, and requested the RMCC make shipper notification via Chem-Trec. While enroute spoke to shipper representative Operations Manager for Husky Oil. He advised the material in the covered hopper car is a solid, not a liquid. This product is used in cracking petroleum crude, and the liquid leaking from the car was a refined oil that is made with the catalyst, and had not been recovered from the waste material. While speaking to  he indicated that he would contact the consignee, Gulf Chemical Metallurgical of Freeport, TX, and have them respond to the area to make repairs to the car. On arrival, met with consignee representative Roddy Mohler, Safety/Transportation Coordinator for Gulf Chemical Metallurgical and several technicians who were working on the car. indicated there was a small hole on the bottom left side of Compartment B, that was being plugged by his personnel. Cause of the hole was due to the bottom edge of the hopper education flange striking an unknown object. While on site was contacted by Material Handling Superintendent for Gulf Chemical Metallurgical. He had made arrangements for Garner Environmental to respond the following day to remediate the affected area. At 21 30hrs, the hole had been plugged with no further release, and the area was cleared. At l000hrs on 3-21-07, Garner Environmental personnel arrived onsite. A surface scrape of the affected area was completed, and Petro-Kleen, a bio remediation material was applied. At 1 23Ohrs the area was cleared, and the car was released to continue onto destination with no further action to be taken. At 164Ohrs the car was switched to the consignee to be off loaded, and bad ordered for necessary repairs.

column168: The driver loaded the truck up, and was getting off the exit ramp from Route 95 to Route 117. The driver was coming to the end of the exit ramp, realized that he was going too fast to stop (with the heavy load), and tried to steer the truck through the traffic light. He made a quick right-hand turn. The truck was full of oil, and top-heavy. The driver appeared to hit the curb, causing the truck to roll over. The tank was crushed in this accident, causing the oil to escape through the top of the fill hatch. It leaked on the roadway for about 1.5 hours. We called Response Environmental, Inc., police, fire, DOT, and the Rescue. Booms were placed near the storm drains. A dump-truck full of sand and gravel were used to make a dam between the truck and the storm drains. The oil then puddled in the middle of the road. The Coast Guard was notified, and booms were placed in the water to collect the oil that did reach the storm drains. DEM, DOT, and the Early Response Teams were there within minutes of this accident.
column169: This accident was beyond my control. This driver has his CDL license with his HAZMAT endorsement.

column168: The Airgas vehicle was eastbound on Booth Road, which begins in an eastward direction and curves north. At this point, Booth Street becomes Benton Street. The Airgas vehicle was en route to the Airgas Searcy, AR facility located at 2229 5. Benton Street, which is approximately 200 ft. northwest of the point of impact. While traveling along the aforementioned curve, the Airgas driver stated that he heard a series of loud “pops” or “bangs” and saw “a flame” behind the cab of the tractor he was driving. The Airgas driver proceeded to exit the vehicle as it was still moving in a northeast direction. The vehicle continued to travel off of BoothlBenton Street in a northeast direction toward Highway 67/167 where it struck a wire fence. The Airgas vehicle continued to travel in a northeast direction into a ditch that borders the west side of Highway 67/167. The vehicle continued to travel onto the southbound lane of Highway 67/167, where it came to a rest crossing both southbound lanes, facing a northeast direction. Vehicle two struck the Airgas vehicle toward the front end of the trailer  The Airgas vehicle (semi-trailer) was loaded with compressed gas cylinders which were secured to steel cylinder pallets via securement straps. Due to the collision impact, many cylinders were thrown out and away from the pallet trailer, including the cylinder cluster discussed in section III. The cylinder cluster in question consists of a steel frame onto which twelve DOT specification cylinders are secured (see attached photos). Each cylinder is connected to a manifold system located at the top of the cluster. Each cylinder is connected to the manifold through 3/8 in. stainless steel braided hose that contain a maximum working pressure of 3000 PSIG. Two of these hoses were sheered as a result of the accident, causing the entire contents (each cylinder) (gaseous nitrogen) to be released to atmosphere. Estimated release duration is 5 — 10 minutes. It is unknown what object caused the manifold to shear.

column168: Vehicle #1 had a flat tire and was driving very slow on the four lane highway. Vehicle #2, our tractor tanker loaded with gasoline, could not stop so he tried to avoid colliding with vehicle #1. Our tractor trailer began to slide and the front of our tractor collided with the left rear of vehicle #1. Our tanker overturned and came to rest on its right side in the median. Motor fuel was leaking out of the dome lids on top of the tanker. We tried to seal the dome lids but could not. The valves to pump off were on the side next to the ground so we could not pump the fuel out of the tanker. We called the county supervisor to bring dirt to dam both sides of the median so we could contain the motor fuel that was leaking out of the tanker. We called US Environmental Services to prepare the tanker to drill holes in it so we could off load the motor fuel. US Environmental prepared the tanker to unload the motor fuel from our tanker to another. The tanker was loaded with 8555 gallons of gasoline. 1540 gallons was released.
column169: I feel that this release was handled in an effective manner to reduce the amount of release and to control the possibilities of further hazards and damages. We will continue to seek better ways to minimize the damages when incidents like this occur. We will continue our training in the areas of safe driving and the controlling of hazardous materials when incidents like this occur.

column168: PART VI- DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS & PACKAGE FAILURE  On 3/30/07 prior to departing facility with a pre loaded tank truck of Sodium Hypochiorite, approximately 5 gallons of product was spilled. column169: PART VII- RECOMMENDATIONS / ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE  Additional training was conducted for all effected drivers, topics discussed:  • Chemical properties of Sodium Hypochiorite  • Vehicle inspections (visual)  • Pre-trip inspections  • Driver communication

column168: Our truck was crossing the railroad tracks in Glendora, MS.  The driver stopped prior to the tracks and did not observe a train.  He then proceeded to cross the tracks when the dolly legs on the trailer got hung up on the asphalt while going across the tracks.  The driver and another gentleman tried to get the truck off of the tracks for a minute or two when they noticed an oncoming train.  The train could not stop and hit the truck/trailer causing it to explode into fire.  The fire burned up the majority of the diesel fuel on the tanker and a small amount of excavation was completed to remove any that may have hit the ground.
column169: The crossing has been re-done after the incident.

column168: Dave O’Neil, Car Foreman, reported a release of product from Tankcar PROX 42044 onto the ground. Tank car was located in the North Platte Yard at Yard One Track 308 at Mile Post 290.84 of the North Platte Terminal. Mr. O’Neil advised the tankcar was leaking continuously from the top at a rate of one gallon every five minutes. Mr. O’Neil stated the tankcar was moved to a concrete containment area and no waterways were affected nor any reported injuries or exposures. Mark Reimers, Regional Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and stated he would contact Kim Keeling to respond. State Regulatory Agency Notifications were made. At 5:25 PM, Keith Martin, Flint Hills Resources advised the product was an aviation gasoline and stated a repair team was en route to inspect the tankcar. At 05:27 PM, Kim Keeling, Manager Environmental Field Operations, reported he was on scene. At 06:34 PM, Keeling stated the leak was due to the liqLlid valve not being secured properly. He resealed the valve and repairs were completed. He also advised he placed seal number UPRR 1133 on the load. Mr. Keeling stated the released product had evaporated. On 3/26 Keeling inspected the car and found it to have seven pounds of pressure with no further leak. Since the valve had been removed the car needed to be inspection by a certified tank car techician. Ryun Vanbasler with AV Fuel (Shipper) at 734-663-6466 ext.304 arranged for Union Tank Car to come to North Platte to perform the inspection. On Thursday, April 5th, Union Tank. car arrived to perform the inspection. The tank car failed inspection and was deemed not certifiable, consequently it would require a transfer. On Monday 4/16 Mr. Keeling and Mr. Vanbasler decided to use a local Haz-Mat Team to do the tranfer. Haz-Mat Response and RMCAT placed bids on the transfer and a bid on cleaning and purging the tank car. Bids were given to AV Fuel for their handling. VanBasler located a tank car in Laramie WY to use for the transfer. UTLX 203004 was routed to North Platte Bailey Yard for the transfer.

column168: UPRR Mechanical Department at El Paso Alfalfa Yard reported Tankcar GATX 6649 was releasing product from top of car. John Jackson, Manager Hazardous Materials, was notified and advised Viva Environmental, Contractor would be dispatched for remediation. Mr. Jackson responded and discovered product had been released due to an open air valve and closure plug not secured. The valve was closed and closure plug secured. Viva personnel cleaned the product from the top of the car. Mr. Jackson re-inspected the car and released it to destination with no other defects noted. Shipper was notified via Chemtrec.

column168: At approximately 1.5 hours into the flight or around 22:20 Local time, a small explosion occurred in the cabin of the aircraft near seats 25-26A1B while enroute from EZE to MIA. Flight Attendants responded with Halon Extinguishers and PBEs per Emergency Procedures in their Flight Manuals however none of this equipment was actually used. Passengers interviewed from the area indicated that there were sparks followed by a flash and smoke. A small battery had exploded splattering debris on the overhead bins above seats 25-26A1B. The Captain responded to notification from a Flight Attendant. Upon his arrival in the Business Class section of the cabin where the explosion occurred the smoke had already cleared. The Captain and several of the Flight Attendants interviewed passengers and conducted a thorough search of the area that included the floor, seat pockets, under the seats and ceiling. The remnants of a battery were all that were found. The Captain collected the largest piece which he later reported appeared to be like a CR123 Lithium battery. He brought this piece of the battery to the cockpit and soon disposed of it in the cockpit trash hag.  A fragment of the exploding battery struck the passenger seated in seat 258 in the head burning the hair on the right side of her head near her ear lobe. She refused any medical treatment. None of the passengers who were interviewed would admit that the battery belonged to them. It is suspected that one of the passengers seated in seats 25-26A/B dropped the battery or moved it with their foot causing itto arch against a seat frame. The flight proceeded to MIA without further incident.  Upon arrival in MIA the seat bottom of 25A was replaced. Upon return to EZE, all seat covers on seats 25 A/B and 26A/B were replaced and the overhead bins were wiped down after photographs were taken. The seat covers were shipped to MIA where they were later turned over to the NTSB for testing for residue.
column169: Increased public awareness such as what has begun at safctravel.dot.gov including TV, radio and newspaper ads is the key to ensuring safer travel with lithium and lithium-ion batteries. Increased awareness by the shipping community will help ensure safe transportation of this commodity as cargo.  Specific limitations on the size of lithium and lithium ion batteries in consumer devices may he necessary until the industry finds a better way to store more power safely.

column168: Freight was being transferred from one ULD to another due to a cut / hole on the side of the unit.  As this freight was being transferred the clerk smelled fuel fumes.  Upon further investigation we found a used engine inside a plastic storage bin.  There was also some oil residue in the bottom of the plastic tub which was used to transport the engine.  The shipment was not labeled as a DG, nor did the AWB or manifest indicate a dangerous good or a special provision.  The manifest states that the HAWB 63889335 is motorcycle parts.  The FAA was immediately notified.  There was additional paperwork that stated "this is to certify that the goods to be shipped have been drained, cleaned, purged of all fluids and is shipped as NOT RESTRICTED as per IATA Section 4.4 Special Provision A70 and IATA Section 5.02.13.5.2 and per 49 CFR 173.220.  The FAA was notified, and Inspector Rich Verplank arrived.  Upon his inspection he did state..."they tried to do the right thing.." but did agree that the shipment was undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment was stored in our dangerous goods storage area and the customer was notified to come pick up the shipment and have it repackaged as dangerous goods and tendered as such.
column169: FAA Inspector Rich Verplank did state that "they tried to do the right thing".  I believe the shipper, Lopez Auto in Garland, Texas, may need training on IATA regulations when shipping used auto parts.  I believe AA responded appropriately in that we detected an undeclared dangerous goods shipment as evident by the smell of gasoline fumes.  We notified the FAA immediately, and stopped the shipment from being placed on another passenger air carrier.

column168: The following paragraph was obtained from the transportation driver’s statement on how the incident occurred. Transportation vehicle was traveling on a mountainous road (Route 10), and negotiating various turns on a downhill grade. After negotiating one turn the unit came to a straight-a-way and entered a left-hand turn. As the unit entered the turn, it met a vehicle traveling in the other lane of traffic. The Flying J Transportation driver kept the vehicle in the appropriate travel lane and negotiated the turn. As the driver came out of the turn, he checked his rearview mirrors and viewed the left rear tires of the trailer were three to four feet off of the road surface. The trailer then flipped to the right causing both tractor and trailer to overturn onto it side. The tractor and trailer slid and completely overturn and exited the road surface into the adjacent highway shoulder (culvert).   According the West Virginia State Police (WVSP), the Investigating Officer claims the following conclusion, "As the vehicle was negotiating a curve, it partially exited the roadway on the east side. As the operator of the vehicle was bringing the vehicle back onto the roadway, he lost control of the same.” SEE CONTINUATION PAGE ATTACHED”
column169: Due to the volume of fuel onboard, approximately 7300 gallons, and the various turns the driver was experiencing, the fuel in the trailer was under constant movement. A trailer transporting liquids will act differently depending upon the volume of fuel. Drivers will be retrained on the proper speeds while traveling on mountainous roadways. This will involve trailers while full, partially full and while empty.

column168: Supervisor’s Report  03/27/07 incident report notes – Terry Church’s Accident    We were notified at roughly 1:30 that Terry had been involved in an accident by a bystander who assisted Terry in getting to a safe distance from the truck after the accident. Bob Schooley was a motorist on the overpass and had seen part of the accident as it was happening. He told me he had seen the truck as it was overturning and wanted to offer assistance. He drove his truck down the off ramp and went towards Terry to help get him away from the truck. He stated the truck had flames on the trailer before it hit the ground. Terry was out of the truck as he got there and heading towards him. He helped him across the off ramp and try to make Terry as comfortable as possible while waiting for emergency personnel. Terry asked him to call the office and his family.   Details were very vague when we started out, did not know Terry’s condition or the location of the accident. I asked a customer in the area to check on what she could as far as letting me know anything. We had bits and pieces of info as the afternoon progressed. I called DNR about 30 minutes after we first were notified, could have called  earlier but did not have enough information to answer any questions.   I spoke with Dean Lamb and began the process of reporting the accident. He assigned a claim number of 0703271350DAL. After taking all the information we had at the time he stated we had done everything we could at that point and would need to work with someone on clean up. Someone from DNR would be on site and tell us what to do and what would be required.   We followed news broadcasts and had information relayed back to us through out the evening. Wayne Schweigert had been in route to Perryville when the first calls came in, he went to the site as soon as he was notified. Wayne and Mark remained in the area until the DNR representative said the clean up procedures had been taken care. I came back to Ozora around 9 pm to assist in setting the tank and making arrangements to be able to unload the water and fuel from the clean up site.   Terry called in the next morning around 7, he was in the hospital and had his medical needs taken care of, but would be in the hospital for a few more days. Although he was in some pain, he sounded good, and had his normal sense of humor.    For more detail see Terry’s statement and police reports.
column169: The driver of the Schweigert Brothers truck was not found at fault in this accident, it is not known at this time if anything on his part could have prevented the incident.

column168: On March 12, 2007, at about 5:00 AM, a truck owned and operated by  Southeast Amalgamated, Inc. (dba Shelton Oil & Transport Co.) wrecked on  Interstate 26 near Exit 37 in Buncombe County, NC. The driver, Steve  Pilkington, died at the scene from trauma caused by the accident.  The tractor-tanker was hauling approximately 8500 gallons of gasoline. The load originated in Spartanburg, SC and was destine for 1-{aywood County, NC.  Evidence from the scene indicates that the truck was west-bound on 1-26 when it came into contact with the guardrail to the right of the driving lane. The truck then proceeded over the guardrail and rolled onto its side due to the slope of the grade adjacent to the roadway. Once on its side, some of the product escaped the tanker through holes caused by the wreck.  Subtracting the quantity of fuel recovered at the scene from the quantity of fuel loaded yields an estimated quantity of 2057 gallons that leaked from the tanker. The product infiltrated the soil at the crash site. The product did not spill into a water body or onto a shoreline. There is no witness or conclusive evidence indicating that any product entered a waterway. Similarly, there has never been an indication of this product on any shoreline.  Any product that would have entered the river would have traveled through a drainage pipe passing underneath the interstate. A grated inlet is connected to this drainage pipe on the side of the interstate where the accident took place. It should be noted that the grated inlet was immediately covered with an impermeable tarp by the EMS first responders to prevent product from entering  this drainagc pipe. This tarp stayed in place from immediately after the accident until the rernecliaion eflos were substantially complete.  As soon as the remaining product was unloaded off of the \\Tecked tmck and the truck removed from the site, rernediation efforts began to clean the crash site. This effort continued until the contaminated soils were removed and hauled to an appropriate landfill.

column168: 1. AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 ON 21 MARCH 2007, A POPE TRANSPORT TRUCKING COMPANY TRUCK #264 WAS OVERFILLED ON TRUCK LOADING SPOT 1 A/B BY AN ESTIMATED AMOUNT OF 150 GALLONS. ALTHOUGH THE SCHULLY OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM INDICATED IT WAS OPERATIONAL (GREEN LIGHT), AN INVESTIGATION BY THE ON-SITE DEFENSE ENERGY SUPPORT CENTER'S GOVERNMENT QUALITY ASSURANCE REPRESENTATIVE REVEALED THAT COMPARTMENTS 2,3 AND 4 DID NOT HAVE OPERATIONAL PROBES/SENSORS. ADDITIONALLY, TWO OTHER POPE TRUCKS WERE TESTED AND TRUCK #433 WAS FOUND TO HAVE TWO BAD PROBES/SENSORS IN COMPARTMENTS 3 AND 4. POPE TRANSPORT TRUCKING COMPANY WAS CONTACTED AND ASKED TO REPLACE THE BAD PROBES/SENSORS PRIOR TO BRINGING THE TRUCKS BACK TO THE TERMINAL.  2. THE ENTIRE SPILL WAS WITHIN THE TRUCK CONTAINMENT AREA AND THE FUEL TRUCK AND CONTAINMENT WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS BY ON-SITE EMPLOYEES. THE REMAINING FUEL WAS DIVERTED TO THE TRUCK RANK OIL WATER SEPARATOR (O/W/S). MORAN ENVIROMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO REMOVE THE FUEL/WATER MIXTURE FROM THE OIL WATER SEPARATOR'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AND DISPOSE OF SPILL PADS IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL LAWS. THEY WERE ALSO COTRACTED TO CLEAN ANY RESIDUE FUEL FROM THE CONTAINMENT LINE AND O/W/S. THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT, INJURIES, EVACUATIONS, ROAD CLOSURES, OR MISSION IMPACT DUE TO THE FUEL SPILL.
column169: NOW THAT WE KNOW THAT SCULLY FAIL-SAFETY INTELETROL SYSTEM CAN (IN SOME CASES) GIVE A GREEN LIGHT INDICATING THE SYSTEM IS FUNCTIONING CORRECTLY WHEN IN REALITY IT IS NOT, WE PERIODICALLY DO A PHYSICAL TEST OF THE VARIOUS TRUCKING COMPANIES PROBES/SENSORS TO DETERMINE WHETHER THEY ARE WORKING CORRECTLY. THOSE TRUCKS FOUND TO HAVE MALFUNCTIONING PROBES/SENSORS WILL BE REJECTED UNTIL THE PROBES ARE REPAIRED OR REPLACED.

On 3-22-07 at approximately 0734 hours, Apria employee driving an Apria 2001 Isuzu FRR, Unit #21300P, MO license 630917, pulled away from a Oxygen, refrigerated liquid stand tank without disconnecting the fill line to the truck mounted nonspecification cryogenic cargo tank. This resulted in the release of approximately 203 gallons of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid from the cargo tank.     Had just completed filling the non-specification cryogenic cargo tank, HL 190 serial #12133 from the 6000 gallons stand tank, serial # 2037. Upon completing the fill he completed the documentation and proceeded to start to move the truck to the parking area not realizing that he had failed to disconnect the fill line. This resulted in damage, with no release, of the piping on the fill mechanism of the stand tank and damage to the fill connection and valve on the non-specification cargo tank which resulted in the release of the 203 gallons of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid, in the tank.     He heard a “pop” as he was starting to pull away and upon looking in his curb side mirror saw the cloud created by the escaping oxygen. He immediately stopped the truck, turned off the ignition and reported the incident to, Branch Logistics Manager. He immediately went to the scene and secured the area from vehicle and pedestrian traffic and instructed his Transportation Supervisor to contact the fire department.     The St. John’s Fire Department arrived at approximately 0746 hours. Fire department personnel evaluated the scene and upon finding that the release was onto a concrete surface and that the liquid was evaporating at a rapid rate determined that there was no further action necessary. At approximately 0801 hours they declared the scene secure and departed.
column169: Driver has received appropriate disciplinary action for his failure to follow Apria Logistics Policy & Procedure #L208-070. Branch Logistics Manager has received appropriate disciplinary action for lack of supervision of the employees and the filling process. All members of the logistics staff at the St Louis facility have received refresher training on the filling process and vehicle control.
